  <summary>A brilliant CIA trainee must prove his worth at the Farm, the agency's secret training grounds, where he learns to watch his back and trust no one.</summary>
  <reviews>
    <item index="0">
      <text>Here I suspected the ultimate villain almost from the very beginning -- and, if I wasn't fooled, I can't imagine anyone else will be, either.</text>
      <source>New York Observer</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.nyobserver.com/pages/story.asp?ID=6938</link>
      <author>Andrew Sarris</author>
    </item>
    <item index="1">
      <text>A conjurer's trick that delights for about an hour, then spirals into idiocy.</text>
      <source>Slate</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.slate.com/id/2077942/</link>
      <author>David Edelstein</author>
    </item>
    <item index="2">
      <text>The Recruit manages to be almost utterly without innovation apart from its heroic determination to make matinee idol material out of a spy agency that pioneered the process of extra-legal bureaucratic sociopathology known as 'black ops.'</text>
      <source>Toronto Star</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://WWW.TheStar.COM/NASApp/cs/ContentServer?&amp;pagename=thestar/Layout/Article_Type1&amp;c=Article&amp;cid=1044010968322&amp;call_pageid=1022183557980&amp;col=1022183560753</link>
      <author>Geoff Pevere</author>
    </item>
    <item index="3">
      <text>The Recruit falters after it leaves the Farm, throwing in unbelievable plot devices and losing its high-wire tension.</text>
      <source>San Francisco Chronicle</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2003/01/31/DD61714.DTL</link>
      <author>Carla Meyer</author>
    </item>
    <item index="4">
      <text>Although The Recruit isn't Len Deighton or Robert Ludlum, it is enjoyable until the screenwriters develop a collective brain cramp.</text>
      <source>ReelViews</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.reelviews.net/movies/r/recruit.html</link>
      <author>James Berardinelli</author>
    </item>
    <item index="5">
      <text>The foreshadowing is a bit heavy-handed, but the writers and director largely manage the tension and mystery tactfully.</text>
      <source>Denver Post</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.denverpost.com/Stories/0,1413,36%257E82%257E1144852%257E,00.html</link>
      <author>Ricardo Baca</author>
    </item>
    <item index="6">
      <text>A serviceable spy thriller that stumbles over one too many plot twists, one too many shots of its hero typing desperately at his computer, and a romantic subplot that's nice to look at but awfully silly.</text>
      <source>Boston Globe</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://ae.boston.com/movies/display?display=movie&amp;id=1871</link>
      <author>Ty Burr</author>
    </item>
    <item index="7">
      <text>The Recruit adds little to the already overworked espionage genre, but it completes its mission, working quietly and stealthily, without drawing too much attention to itself.</text>
      <source>Detroit Free Press</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://ae.freep.com/entertainment/ui/michigan/movie.html?id=87718&amp;reviewId=11083</link>
      <author>John Monaghan</author>
    </item>
    <item index="8">
      <text>It's the kind of movie you can sit back and enjoy, as long as you don't make the mistake of thinking too much.</text>
      <source>Chicago Sun-Times</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-recruit-2003</link>
      <author>Roger Ebert</author>
    </item>
  </reviews>
